AB  - Aquaculture households face severe economic and livelihood challenges because of the combined effects of typhoon disasters and aging in the island regions of China. A critical aspect of disaster risk management is knowledge of socioeconomic vulnerability at the local level. However, research on the economic vulnerability of aquaculture households to typhoon disasters at the local scale is scarce. This study aims to examine the economic vulnerability of aquaculture households of elderly people to typhoon disasters and the factors influencing it, based on data obtained from household surveys in island regions of Southeast China. The analytical results demonstrated that aquaculture households of elderly people in island regions show high eco-nomic vulnerability to typhoon disasters and are more vulnerable than households with younger heads. Employing the fuzzy-set qualitative comparative analysis method, this study identified eight configurations, involving the education level, health status, number of household persons engaged in aquaculture, and number of typhoon experiences in the past five years as the key factors leading to high economic vulnerability of aquaculture households of elderly people to typhoon disasters. The results also revealed complex interactions among these key factors, and the dependence of households on aquaculture, government subsidies, and credit loans contributes to their high economic vulnerability. This study provides new insights into the complex causes of economic vulnerability to typhoon disasters at the household level and the particularity of the aquaculture households of elderly people in island regions. These findings have implications for effectively reducing vulnerability and enhancing disaster adaption processes of aquaculture farmers in developing countries.
