TI  - Assessing marine sustainability in the Gulf Region: A comparative analysis using the ocean health index with a focus on Oman
T2  - FOOD AND HUMANITY
LA  - English
KW  - Sustainable development
KW  - Marine sustainability
KW  - Life below water
KW  - SDG 14
KW  - Gulf region
KW  - DEVELOPMENT GOALS
KW  - COASTAL
KW  - SEA
AB  - The Persian/Arabian Gulf supports vital marine ecosystems critical to fisheries, tourism, and coastal livelihoods but faces mounting pressure from urbanization, overfishing, climate change, and pollution. This study evaluates marine sustainability across eight Gulf countries-the six GCC states, Iran, and Iraq-using the Ocean Health Index (OHI), which integrates ecological, economic, and social indicators. Results show significant disparities: the UAE and Qatar lead overall, while Iran and Iraq lag behind. Oman performs moderately, excelling in livelihoods and coastal protection but struggling with fisheries and carbon storage. The analysis provides a regional baseline for monitoring progress toward SDG 14and identifies priority areas for improving marine governance. We also emphasize evidence-based policy integration and cross-border cooperation to strengthen the Gulf's blue economy.
