AB  - Egyptian clover, oats and alfalfa are cultivated for feed and green fodder during winter in Punjab and other regions of the country. Although, these crops are adapted to most of the regions in India, diseases viz., stem rot, leaf blight and down mildew impose significant green fodder and seed yield losses especially to dairy farmers. Weather parameters play a crucial role in the infection and dissemination of pathogens. The effect of weather attributes on the progression of diseases was studied during winter for seven years from 2015-16 to 2021-22. Weather variables like temperature, relative humidity, rainfall, evaporation, and sunshine hours were taken to record their effect on disease development. The highest mean stem rot incidence ranged between 33.0 and 68.5% during week 50 (second week of December) and assessed maximum up to week 12 (third week of March). During the disease recording period the mean weekly temperature varied from 5.2 to 26.5 degrees C, relative humidity from 46.6 to 94.3%, rainfall, sunshine hours and total evaporation varied from 1.6 to 22.3 mm, 2.4 to 8.0 h and 7.5 to 27.2 mm day- 1 respectively. Oat leaf blight severity ranged between 49.87 and 70.58% during week 1 (first week of January) and recorded maximum till week 15 (second week of April). Maximum downy mildew incidence ranged from 40.12 to 59.45% in six years of study time, weekly intervals starting from week 2 (second week of January) to week 14 (first week of April). Heatmaps between weather variables and disease severity showed a significant positive correlation of severity with maximum and minimum temperature and evaporation and a significant negative correlation with morning and evening relative humidity. It showed that disease incidence or severity progresses with the increase in maximum and minimum temperature and evaporation, whereas it was also noted that disease incidence was observed maximum in afternoon.
