AB  - Sandy beaches are socially relevant ecosystems that provide multiple services yet face escalating threats from climate change, unregulated resource use, and coastal urbanization. This study presents a four-decade, multiscale assessment of how human pressures have reshaped the ecological condition and social perception of the La Coronilla-Barra del Chuy coastal system (Uruguay). A mixed-methods framework integrating long-term ecological datasets, satellite-derived demographic indicators, census information, expert elicitation, and local ecological knowledge across three sites with contrasting human impacts enabled a cross-validated diagnosis of environmental degradation and its social implications within this sandy beach social-ecological system. Results revealed a clear spatial gradient of alteration: the non-urbanized Control site retained the widest beach, highest salinity, and greatest biodiversity, serving as a baseline for natural conditions. In contrast, La Coronilla exhibited severe physical, chemical, and biological deterioration linked to chronic freshwater and pollutant inputs from the discharge of a man-made canal, while Barra del Chuy showed intermediate conditions influenced by urbanization and tourism. Long-term records of the filter-feeding guild (Mesodesma mactroides, Donax hanleyanus, Emerita brasiliensis) evidenced sustained declines in abundance, biomass, and body size, indicating functional impoverishment under freshwater and nutrient stress. Local ecological knowledge corroborated these findings. Management priorities include reducing nutrient inputs, restoring dune integrity to enhance natural defenses, regulating tourism infrastructure and clam harvesting, and incorporating citizen monitoring into planning and decision-making. Integrating quantitative and qualitative evidence advances coastal research from diagnosis to transformation, offering an operational framework to foster resilience and adaptive governance in sandy beach systems worldwide.
