TI  - Leveraging satellite imagery for comprehensive agro-economic health assessment in Indian villages: A case study of Karnataka's diverse agro-climatic zones
T2  - REMOTE SENSING APPLICATIONS-SOCIETY AND ENVIRONMENT
LA  - English
KW  - Agro-economic health
KW  - Remote sensing
KW  - Machine learning
KW  - Economic Health Score (EHS)
KW  - Indian village
KW  - SAR
AB  - India has historically been a prominent agricultural nation globally. However, in the twenty-first century, India faces the dual challenges of increasing productivity and ensuring sustainability. The adoption of precision agriculture may not be feasible due to the low average monthly income of rural farmers, which was determined to be just Rs 10,218 or $127 according to the SAS (Situational Assessment Survey, 2018). Therefore, it is crucial to develop methods to closely monitor the agro-economic conditions at village level in order to understand the gaps and curate better strategies. To address this, a comprehensive framework has been developed that utilizes satellite imagery and other relevant environmental and socioeconomic factors to assess the agroeconomic health of Indian villages. This framework has been demonstrated in five hoblies (groups of villages), representing different agro-climatic zones in Karnataka. The analysis has been conducted for the hoblies of Agara (Southern Dry zone), Mudhola (Northern Dry zone), Kasaba (Central Dry Zone), Nippani (Northern Transition Zone), and Holluru (Eastern Dry Zone). The Economic Health Score (EHS) has been computed as an indicator of the overall agro-economic situation at the village level, based on the general agricultural practices observed in these hoblies from 2019 to 2022. The calculation of the EHS takes into account various factors, including satellite-derived factors such as crop health, moisture content, and percentage of agricultural area, as well as socio-economic and environmental factors like transportation facilities, irrigation coverage, rainfall, and climate change. Satellite-derived factors are obtained through the utilization of Sentinel-2 (Optical) and Sentinel-1 (Microwave) satellite data. This is achieved by employing machine learning-based classification models as well as methods based on vegetative indices. Appropriate weightage was assigned to each independent contributing factor using Analytical Hierarchical Process (AHP) for determining EHS. The findings revealed that Nippani hobli, located in the Belgaum region within the Northern transition zone, achieved the highest EHS score of 77 out of 100. Conversely, Holluru hobli, situated in the Kolar region in the Eastern Dry agro-climatic zone, recorded the lowest EHS score of 46 out of 100. The analysis demonstrates a strong correlation between regional geography, cropping patterns and the computed EHS, providing insights into the actual ground conditions. Nevertheless, further refinement and upscaling of the analysis could be achieved by incorporating more detailed nearreal time field level datasets from various villages across India.
