AB  - Agroforestry systems are recognized as an effective land-use strategy for enhancing soil carbon sequestration and promoting sustainable agricultural development. However, the mechanisms associated with soil organic carbon (SOC) stabilization in rubber-based agroforestry systems within the tropics are not fully understood. Based on a double-row rubber plantation established by using rubber tree clone (CATAS 7-20-59) in 2002, a long-term field experiment was conducted in Hainan, China, this study investigated the distribution and stability of soil aggregates and their associated SOC content across different rubber plantation configurations. The treatments included a monoculture rubber plantation (RM) and six agroforestry systems: Hevea brasiliensis intercropped with Theobroma cacao (TCA), Alpinia oxyphylla (AOM), Alpinia katsumadai Hayata (AKH), Cinnamomum cassia (L.) D. Don. (CCA), Pandanus amaryllifolius Roxb (PAR), and Coffea arabica (CAA). Compared with the RM, the CAA, CCA and TCA systems significantly enhanced SOC storage within the 0-60 cm layer by 6.35 %, 15.03 %, and 19.79 %, respectively, whereas the AOM and AKH treatments conversely decreased it by 14.59 % and 8.88 %. Macroaggregates (0.25-2 mm) constituted the primary SOC pool, accounting for 49.09-60.51 % of total SOC, followed by microaggregate (< 0.25 mm, 22.63-25.23 %) and large aggregate (>2 mm, 16.86-26.04 %). Intercropping with herbaceous to arboreal species significantly increased the proportion of large and macroaggregates, as well as the geometric mean diameter (GMD) and mean weight diameter (MWD) across soil depths and planting patterns, indicating enhanced SOC stability along the gradient from herbaceous to arboreal systems. Soil physicochemical properties, aggregate stability, enzyme activities, and mineral content collectively explained approximately 89 % of the observed variation in SOC, with aggregate stability and mineral content identified as the most influential factors. These findings suggest that rubber tree-arboreal agroforestry systems represent a promising management practice for enhancing soil carbon sequestration and sustainability in rubber plantation on Hainan Island. By quantitatively strengthening the soil carbon sink capacity, such systems can contribute to "carbon neutrality" objectives and offers a scientific basis for climate change mitigation. Furthermore, the potential generation of carbon credits through these systems may provide additional economic incentives for local farmers and plantation managers, thereby fostering more sustainable rubber production the land-use practices.
