KW  - WATER
AB  - This study investigated the pastoralists' indigenous knowledge on livestock production, trends and their perceptions of rangeland degradation and its indicators in Omaandi, Epukunoyana and Oshitutuma in central northern Namibia. A total of 30 households that own livestock and two elder groups were selected from each communal area. A questionnaire was used to gather household information, and an open-ended discussion was conducted to interview elders. Data were analysed using SPSS statistical software programme (SPSS version 22 2015), where the Friedman's Chi-square test (Steel and Torrie, 1980) was used. The majority of interviewed households in Omaandi (63%), Oshitutuma (53%) and Epukunoyana (50%) were female headed families and the remaining were male headed. The mean population of goats and cattle were significantly higher (P < 0.05) in Omaandi and Epukunoyana than in Oshitutuma village. Household respondents in all villages indicated that all livestock species were primarily kept for wealth status and meat provision for consumption. Respondents in all villages indicated that lack of grazing lands and feed followed by water scarcity and recurring droughts were the primary and secondary constraints of livestock production. Elder respondents regarded overgrazing and climate change as the primary cause of rangeland degradation. Hence, the study concludes that communal rangelands are degraded and degradation resulted in gradual livestock population declining trends over the past years in communal areas, due to feed shortage.
