KW  - climate finance
KW  - nationally determined contributions
KW  - climate smart agriculture
KW  - private finance
KW  - Africa
KW  - PROJECTS
AB  - This study investigates how Public-Private Partnerships (PPPs) mobilize climate finance and enhance Climate-Smart Agriculture (CSA) to support Nationally Determined Contributions (NDCs) in Kenya and Senegal. Using a comparative exploratory-normative research design, the research combines document analysis, project reports, and secondary data on PPP investments, CSA adoption, and NDC implementation between 2015 and 2024. Both countries have established enabling environments for private sector engagement, yet their approaches and outcomes differ. In Kenya, comprehensive climate legislation and structured programmes such as the Kenya Climate-Smart Agriculture Project (KCSAP) enabled PPPs to reach over 600,000 farmers, increase productivity by 40%, and expand solar-powered irrigation systems. Senegal, by contrast, deployed participatory, farmer-focused PPP models that mobilized $50 million, generated carbon credits worth $10 million annually, and supported large-scale agroforestry with 15 million trees planted, although country-level data remain less detailed. Shared challenges include fragmented climate data, limited monitoring systems, and gaps in gender inclusivity. Kenya benefits from legislative coherence and large-scale implementation, whereas Senegal excels in participatory approaches and localized financing. The findings highlight both convergent and divergent lessons, offering practical insights for designing context-sensitive PPP strategies to scale CSA and accelerate NDC achievement in sub-Saharan Africa.
